node.text:
Your #stargazing #guide for this month is here.🔭

September's #night #sky brings us two "fast" #stars: speedy #Arcturus and fast-spinning #Altair. Follow the #BigDipper's handle to "arc to Arcturus" in the northwest and look for Altair hanging above #Saturn toward the south.

So catch them if you can, and if you’re up for another challenge, try to spot #Mercury in the beginning of the month. You’ll have to be quick! Depending on your latitude, Mercury may be visible very low near the western horizon half an hour after sunset, though you might need binoculars to find it in the fading light. The farther south you are, the better chance you'll have to spot it.

More #skywatching tips here: go.nasa.gov/3zLnOgh (link in bio)

node.text:
The landscape is changing as our #Curiosity #Mars #rover continues to climb Mount Sharp!

Knobbly rocks and rounded hills are starting to appear just as we’re leaving one region of enriched clay materials and entering another with salty minerals called #sulfates. The changes are clues to how this part of the mountain became drier in the ancient past.

Curiosity landed nine years ago on Aug. 5, 2012, to study whether different #Martian environments could have supported microbial life in the planet’s past, when lakes and groundwater existed within Gale Crater.

node.title: NASA's Curiosity Mars Rover Finds a Changing Landscape

node.text:
Skywatching tips for August.🤩 

Look up to see a “blue moon,” it'll be the third full Moon out of four this season, where normally each season only has three. This happens every two-and-a-half to three years, or as they say..."once in a blue moon."

You’ll be able to catch the best-known meteor shower of the year, the Perseids, mid-month, peaking on August 12. August is also perhaps the best time this year to enjoy viewing Jupiter and Saturn, as both planets reach opposition. 

"Opposition" is the term for when a planet is on the same side of the solar system as Earth, and directly opposite from the Sun. Around this time, the planet is visible from sunset to sunrise, and reaches its highest point in the sky around midnight. Opposition is also near the time Earth is closest to the planet, or planets in this case, so this is when they tend to look their biggest and brightest.

node.text:
The scientific heart of the international water-monitoring satellite SWOT, which was assembled in the JPL Spacecraft Assembly Facility, is now in Cannes, France. There, engineers and techs will spend the next year integrating hardware with the rest of the instrument.
 
SWOT is a collaboration between NASA and the French space agency @cnes, with contributions from the @canadianspaceagency and @spacegovuk. This satellite will make global surveys of Earth’s surface water. By measuring its height, researchers can track the volume and location of the finite resource around the world. 
 
It is scheduled to launch in late 2022.

Here’s a closer look at one of the instruments @NASA’s Perseverance Mars rover is using to study the rocks and soil in its pristine environment.
 
Mounted on the "head" of the rover's long-necked mast, SuperCam features a rock-vaporizing laser, camera, and microphone that helps the rover seek organic compounds that could be related to past life on Mars. It can identify the chemical and mineral makeup of targets as small as a pencil point from a distance of more than 20 feet (7 meters).

node.text:
🌄 Cleaner air.
 
A study focused on the early months of the #COVID19 lockdowns found that lower emissions dropped global ozone levels to a place that policymakers thought would take at least 15 years to reach by conventional means, such as regulations. Nitrogen oxide emissions (NOx), which create ozone pollution, decreased 15% globally and as much as 50% locally.
 
Ozone protects us from destructive solar radiation when it’s high above Earth in the stratosphere. But closer to the ground, ozone has other lasting impacts. Ozone at the surface was estimated to cause 365,000 deaths globally in 2019 by damaging the lungs of vulnerable people, such as young children and those who have asthma. It also damages the breathing systems of plants, which is their ability to photosynthesize. That damage reduced plant growth and crop yields.
 
When the world began to go into lockdown, scientists were given a unique opportunity to study how human activity interacts with natural Earth system processes at regional and global levels. A team of researchers focused on the two main oxides of nitrogen: nitrogen oxide and nitrogen dioxide. They charted the chain of events from reduced fossil fuels burning during lockdowns to reduced local NOx emissions and finally to reduced global tropospheric ozone pollution. They found that the stricter lockdowns showed greater reductions in emissions.
 
The total result of the reduced NOx emissions was a 2% drop in global ozone – half the amount that the most aggressive NOx emission controls considered by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change were expected to produce over a 30-year period.
 
Researchers also used measurements of NOx, ozone and other atmospheric gases from five @NASA and @ESA Earth-observing satellites. They fed the observations into four numerical methods of atmospheric chemical reactions and weather, finding that changes in the models’ atmospheres matched the satellite observations and reproduced known increases and decreases in emissions as regions went in and out of lockdowns.

✨
 
In June, the after-dark wonders bring us the constellation Scorpius, a Strawberry Moon, Saturn and Jupiter visible in the south at dawn, and a partial solar eclipse visible in the Northeastern U.S. 
 
And for more excitement this month, @NASA's Juno spacecraft is making its next close flyby over Jupiter, and this time it will also make a low-altitude flyby over the planet-sized icy moon Ganymede.

This is the first of several planned flybys of the Jovian moons – including icy Europa and volcanic Io – that Juno will make over the next couple years.
 
More on what to look up to at night: go.nasa.gov/34hp376

NISAR, a joint @NASA-@ISRO.IN Earth-observing mission, will track the subtle changes in our planet’s surface and spot warning signs of volcanic eruptions.

The satellite will monitor these changes in Earth’s surface over nearly the entire globe. This type of monitoring has not been done before with the high resolution in space and time that NISAR will deliver.

NISAR is set for launch no earlier than 2022.

The Martian surface in 3D 👓

#MarsHelicopter captured this rocky outcrop during its 13th flight. The geologic target, which was dubbed “Faillefeu” after a medieval abbey in the French Alps, has been a spot of interest for the #Perseverance #Mars #rover team.

About 33 feet (10 meters) wide, the mound is visible just north of the center of the image, with some large rocks casting shadows. A portion of “Artuby,” a ridgeline more than half a mile (900 meters) wide, is stretched across the image at the top.

The #MarsHelicopter is prepping for flight 14, which will be no earlier than Friday, Sept. 17.

#Ingenuity performed a rotor spin test at 2,800 rpm on Wednesday, Sept. 15. Next up – a short test hop where it’s expected to climb 16 feet, perform a small sideways movement and then land. But Chief Pilot Håvard Grip said results from the significant rpm changes could help the #rotorcraft continue its scouting efforts for the #Perseverance #rover in lower atmospheric densities.

Take a spin in 3D and even track the Perseverance rover. Two interactive web experiences let you explore the Martian surface, as seen by cameras aboard the rover and orbiters flying overhead.

node.text:
Long ago, Mars was rocked by thousands of volcanic eruptions. 🌋
 
#Scientists found evidence that a northern region called Arabia Terra experienced thousands of "super #eruptions," the biggest and most violent #volcanic eruptions known over a 500-million-year period about 4 billion years ago.
 
After blasting the equivalent of 400 million Olympic-size swimming pools of molten rock and gas through the #Martian surface and spreading a thick blanket of ash up to thousands of miles from the eruption site, a #volcano of this magnitude collapses into a giant hole called a “#caldera.” Calderas, which also exist on #Earth, can be dozens of miles wide.
 
Seven calderas in #ArabiaTerra were the first giveaways that the region may once have hosted #volcanoes capable of super eruptions.
 
#NASA #JPL #GSFC

node.text:
It takes a village when #SamplingMars.

The #Perseverance #rover team has a sample shepherd, a person who coordinates and consults with various rover teams during sampling. This significant role helps to choose and explore the rocks as well as other interesting targets in ways that are safe, doable, appropriately timed and meet the mission’s science goals.

Justin Simon, a @nasajohnson planetary #scientist, was chosen to be the #Mars2020 team’s first shepherd. He recalled learning how missions are conducted, studying images and other materials on #Mars, and participating in scenario testing and training sessions to figure out the best ways to conduct science with the rover.

On Sept. 6, he was part of the historic moment when Perseverance collected its first sample and again when it collected its second sample from the same rock two days later.

#history #research #SolarSystem #NASA #JPL

See Mars in 3D! 👓
 
This mosaic image shows a rock outcrop in the "Citadelle" area on the floor of Jezero Crater. It was composed of multiple images taken by @NASA’s Perseverance rover using its Mastcam-Z instrument.
 
The mosaic image has been nicknamed "Malamaire" by the rover team and includes a block of rock called "Rochette" (after "La Rochette," a small town in north-central France whose name also translates to "little rock"). Perseverance successfully collected its first two rock samples from Rochette earlier this month.
 
Don’t have 3D glasses handy? Here’s how you can make some at home: go.nasa.gov/3A91TjX (link in bio)

DYK @NASA’s Perseverance rover’s hobbies include #photography, collecting #rocks, #offroading and puzzle-solving?

The rover is currently piecing together #Mars’ history. The rocks it has analyzed for sample collection are helping the team better understand a past marked by #volcanic activity and #water.

After the #rover successfully collected its first pair of rock samples, scientists are already gaining new insights into #Jezero #Crater. The rock that provided the mission’s first core samples may be the product of #lava flows. Further analysis may help the team piece together the timeline of the region's past.

More on how #Perseverance is playing detective: go.nasa.gov/3k0mQb1

Great news! @NASA’s Sun Radio Interferometer Space Experiment (#SunRISE) passed a key mission review on Sept. 8, moving the mission into its next phase of development. 

Consisting of six toaster-size solar-powered #spacecraft known as #CubeSats, the SunRISE constellation will operate together as one large #telescope – forming the first space-based imaging low radio frequency interferometer – to create 3D maps pinpointing how giant bursts of energetic particles originate from the #Sun and evolve as they expand outward into #space.
 
The mission will also map, for the first time, how the Sun’s magnetic field extends into space – a key factor that drives where and how storms move throughout the #SolarSystem. Solar storms can be a radiation hazard to satellites and astronauts in space, and can affect power grids on Earth. SunRISE will help scientists understand how #SolarStorms are generated and how they travel through the solar system.
 
Head to the link in bio to read more: go.nasa.gov/3l9q7UN

Today was a good day.😎
 
@NASA’s #Perseverance #Mars #rover successfully acquired its second sample of the #RedPlanet. It’s a paired sample from “Rochette,” the same rock we took our first sample from. The end-to-end sample acquisition worked in a single #Martian day, (a #sol), thus making that a total of two #samples collected in one week.
 
The core acquired is 6.15 cm.
